1 prevention, including health professionals, shall develop and make available on the office of public instruction's
2 website an information sheet describing cardiac arrest symptoms and warning signs, including the risks
3 associated with continuing to play or practice after experiencing cardiac arrest symptoms and warning signs.
4 The superintendent of public instruction is encouraged to collaborate with the athletic association, conference,
5 or organization with authority over interscholastic sports in the state in developing materials under this
6 subsection (2) to ensure consistency in information provided to schools, coaches, athletic trainers, and officials.
7 (3) (a) Beginning in the 2026-2027 school year, in accordance with guidelines set forth by either
8 the American heart association or other nationally recognized, evidence-based standards, each school district
9 and nonpublic school with an athletic department or organized athletic program shall develop a standalone
10 cardiac emergency response plan, or embed a cardiac emergency response protocol within the school safety
11 plan or emergency operations plan, that is venue specific and addresses the appropriate use of school
12 personnel to respond to incidents involving an individual experiencing cardiac arrest or a similar life-threatening
13 emergency while attending or participating in a school-sponsored athletic practice or event.
14 (b) The plan must integrate, at a minimum, the following elements:
15 (i) establishing a cardiac emergency response team;
16 (ii) activating the team in response to a sudden cardiac arrest;
17 (iii) making a clearly marked automated external defibrillator easily accessible in an unlocked
18 location at each school athletic venue and event. The automated external defibrillators must be accessible
19 during the school day and at any school-sponsored athletic event or team practice in which pupils of the school
20 are participating. The automated external defibrillators must be tested and maintained according to the
21 manufacturer's operational guidelines, and notification must be provided to the appropriate first aid, ambulance,
22 or rescue squad or other appropriate emergency medical services provider regarding the defibrillator, the type
23 acquired, and its location.
24 (iv) disseminating the plan throughout the school campus;
25 (v) maintaining ongoing hands-on staff training in cardiopulmonary resuscitation, first aid, and the
26 use of an automatic external defibrillator;
27 (vi) practicing annually through the use of drills;
28 (vii) integrating local emergency medical services with the plan; and
